maml:description.maml:para: {{Returns all devices (limiited to 2,500) listed in PRTG for a given group via the Group ID.}}

{{Returns all devices (limiited to 2,500) listed in PRTG for a given group via the Group ID. The default group is the root group (ID=0). It is important to remember that in PRTG a group can also be a device, probe, etc.}}

{{The ID of the group to query the sensors of.}}

command:example.maml:title: -------------------------- Example 1 --------------------------
command:example.dev:code: PS C:\> {{ Get-PRTGDevicesInGroup -GroupID "8001"}}

dev:remarks.maml:para: {{ By specifying the starting ID of "8001", we will get all PRTG devices that belong to that group's ID. }}

maml:description.maml:para: {{Creates environment variables to store API authentication string and server location.}}

{{Set-PRTGServer uses built-in environment variables to create authentication details for the PRTG Server. The authentication string consists of some syntax as well as the username and password hash of an API user. See PRTG documentation for more details on how to create these. The server parameter is any FQDN, Computer Name, or IP Address of your PRTG server that you can use to access it. Keep in mind that if you use something like the Computer Name then decide to move off network, you won't be able to make API calls to your server.}}

command:example.maml:title: -------------------------- Example 1 --------------------------
command:example.dev:code: PS C:\> {{Set-PRTGServer}}

dev:remarks.maml:para: {{The only use for this cmdlet is to call it natively. It has no parameters or other inputs/outputs.}}
